  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Readability is the degree to which a text can be understood by its intended audience. The term covers both quantitative measures (readability formulas) and qualitative judgments about clarity, organization, and usability.\nRudolf Flesch pioneered quantitative readability research with the Flesch Reading Ease score and (with J. Peter Kincaid) the Flesch-Kincaid Grade Level, which estimate text difficulty from sentence length and syllable count [@flesch1949]. These formulas made readability measurable and became the most widely used metrics in English.\n",
